elinesg7]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>keto weight loss &amp; mock potato soup</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/wOjyS9K</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/MlX9xEg.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/E1mMFa8.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>cook bacon bits</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/N9YGXvB.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>consult sous chef on doneness</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/7FizWQH.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>set aside for later</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/cDuob9C.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>i left all the bacon grease because yolo, add two celery stalks and one yellow onion</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/KBGveHI.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>add salt and pepper and i added butter ??, cook for ten min on medium</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/MXV6HWL.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>add whole head of cauli flower, and minced garlic (i did five cloves ?) cover in broth of your choice</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/aHCXOdv.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>After the cauliflower is soft as f immersion blend (i took out about a 1/4 cup of the broth before blended to retain thiccness)</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/l02s3jj.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Add cheese and heavy cream and then blend again</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/nq7TYEG.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Garnish with the bacon, some more cheese, green onions, and some crème fraiche</div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/wOjyS9K</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[shinebrightlike]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>It's disgusting how grossly misinformed people are about this.</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/hE3Yxxr</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/GFyzgyY.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Okay okay, this is a bit of a rant post, so TLDR: Reactors arent nukes, and its hard for them to go chernobyl now. We need them if we want to fix the planet.

Every time I talk to people online about this people always end up going back to Chernobyl or Fukushima. The truth is it's a lot more complicated than that. Rules about safety are written in blood, thats how everything has worked since the beginning of our civilization. Just like how natural gas is made to smell like rotten eggs because in victorian england it was odorless and caused asphixiation, house fires and explosions. Modern nuclear reactors are built with many contingincies in place to stop nuclear engineers from accidentally causing a meltdown. 

Now lets talk about chernobyl
The soviet government controlling ukraine at the time was hopelessly corrupt, that paired with the severely flawed design of the soviet reactors and human error caused by the engineers working with already outdated technology lead to the worst Nuclear accident in the history of the world. This accident wasnt unforseen however, the nuclear plant had procedures against the actions of the engineers, who ran the plant at extremely low power without following safety precautions and without proper communication.
These reactors were also highly unstable at low power due to how they were designed, even so the power plant continued to be used for 14 years after the meltdown until it was shut down in the year 2000, however it remains in decommission to this day.
Normally a disaster response would be immediate, but the Soviet government was more concerned with covering up the disaster instead of starting evacuation so many preventable deaths were caused as a result.
To sum it up, the chernobyl disaster was caused by a perfect storm of ineptitude from all parties involved.

Fukushima is a little less stupid, but was still preventable. The diesel generators that ran the pumps could have easily kept running if they had been built on higher ground. As well when the plant was built they did not pay enough attention to the risk of a tsunami, despite the plant being in a prime spot for such a disaster to occur, had they built proper protections the damage could have been greatly limited. That and the fact that the nuclear agency in charge of the plant botched the response with unnecessary beurocracy.

Now lets talk about everyone's favorite talking point.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/2aoE1iU.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>The forbidden radio cake.
Actually this is what nuclear waste looks like
Nuclear waste isnt some green sludge that is pumped from reactors into rivers, instead it's the spent Uranium fuel after being reenriched many times to go through the reactor again. After a few times being spent of its usefulness fissile material is packed into dirt and sand, then shipped off for storage. Where you might ask? well we simply stick it right back in the ground where it came from in the first place and seal it up. All that radiation stays in the bedrock and causes almost no pollution if disposed of properly. Remember that uranium is just a metal that we take out of the earth's crust, there's no reason we cant put it back there when we're done with it.

Now a lot of people are scared living next to a nuclear power plant will cause you to get radiation poisoning, this actually couldnt be further from the truth. Major accidents are very rare, only 2 class 7 accidents have ever happened in history, so a modern power plant will be totally safe to live near and wont cause your family any problems.
What you should be worried about are coal power plants. I know it sounds weird but a coal power plant actually emits more radiation into its surrounding area than a nuclear power plant ever will in its normal operating life.
Nuclear power plants are also safer than all of our other forms of power generation, while fossil fuel cause tens of thousands of deaths a year, nuclear energy causes less than 1 death every year due to how safe it's become.
If we're going to fix our environment, we have to use the resources we have at our disposal now, we have a clean and safe was to produce all of our energy but we're not using it, Nuclear power plants have a tiny carbon footprint and are reliable enough to completely replace fossil fuels, we just need to actually use them instead of shutting them all down.

Fp edit: alright, there are many points here i missed, or worded poorly, ill be making a follow up post addressing these and expanding on the nuclear waste point</div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/hE3Yxxr</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[FistingWithJalapenoDoritoFingers]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Insulin</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/FxxY3S7</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/RK5hhXa.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/FxxY3S7</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[mfrybeasley]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Dogs reacting to their names being called -- Dogs are the best people. :)</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/GqlkhOB</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/0lhoGia.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Part l</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/YvzL8ms.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Source : 
